ce:section.ce:para:
The crystal and molecular structures of as-prepared CCN and CDs/CCN samples were further characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD) and Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR). It can be seen from XRD diagrams in Fig. 2
                        a and b that all samples have typical characteristic peaks at around 13.2° and 27.2°, corresponds to the (100) plane of the CN structure (the in-plane order of triazine units) and the (002) plane (i.e., periodic accumulation of layers along the c-axis) [26–28], which proved that the modified samples retained the crystal structure of carbon nitride after carbon-doping in the CN network and CDs loading on the surface of CN. Note that no diffraction peaks belonging to the carbon material obtained from gelatin pyrolysis were observed at 25.2° and 43.7° [29,30]. The full XRD spectra of CCN-x and the high resolution XRD spectra of (002) are shown in Fig. 2a, and the diffraction peak of (002) appears slightly redshift and strengthen after carbon-doping, indicating that after gelatin pyrolysis provides external C atoms for the system to increase the C element content, resulting in the reduced crystal plane spacing of tris-triazine units [31,32]. However, with the introduction of the CDs, the diffraction characteristic peaks of the CDs/CCN-5 have significantly different patterns from those of the CCN (Fig. 2b). The (100) peak intensity of the CDs/CCN-5 photocatalyst was not obvious or even disappeared, which is related to the strong interfacial interaction between CDs and CCN and the porous structure periodically breaking the in-plane structure, and a similar phenomenon was observed in porous g-C3N4 nanosheets [33]. The redshift phenomenon of the diffraction peak of the (002) still exists, indicating that the introduction of CDs can also increase the layer spacing [34]. Different from the XRD patterns of CN and CCN, (002) the diffraction peaks are significantly broadened with the increase of CDs content, and the peak intensity increases, indicating that the loading of CDs leads to grain refinement of CN and increases the content of C element in CCN samples [35]. Fig. 2c exhibits the FT-IR spectra of the prepared samples, and the peak at 812 cm−1 is the respiratory vibration of the heptazine ring in CN networks, the peaks at 1200–1650 cm−1 belong to the tensile vibration mode of C-N/C = N heterocycles, and the peaks at around 2900 ∼ 3300 cm−1 are caused by the tensile vibrations of N-Hx (x = 1 or 2) [36–38]. All samples have nearly identical characteristic peaks, indicating that neither the doping of C atoms nor the loading CDs changes the crystal structure of the CN substrate and is unaffected by thermal polymerization. The chemical constituent of CN, CCN-5 and 0.5-CDs/CCN-5 were determined by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) technique. As exhibited in Fig. S7 and Table S1, CN, CCN-5 and 0.5-CDs/CCN-5 all include three basic elements including C, N and a small amount of O element [39,40]. Notably, after the doping carbon into the original CN, the C element content increased significantly, the atomic ratio increased from 49.23% to 58.83%, and the introduction of CDs further increased the C content to 59.75%. Fig. 2d shows the C 1 s spectra of as-prepared samples, convolving into three peaks (see Table S2), corresponding to C-C/C = C, C-O and N-C = N [41,42], respectively. It is noteworthy that the C-C/C = C peak intensity and peak area of CNC-5 are significantly increased, with the binding energy shifted in a higher direction compared to CN, indicating that internal doping of C atoms derived gelatin pyrolysis led to a change in electronic structure[43]. As can be seen in Fig. 2e, the N 1 s spectra can be deconvoluted into four characteristic peaks for C-N = C, N-(C)3, C-N-H and π excitations (See Table S3) [44,45]. The binding energies of C-N = C for CCN-5 shifted to the binding energy and the significant reduction in the elemental N content in the full XPS spectrum could indicate that the adjacent N atoms may be replaced by C atoms. For the N 1 s spectrum of 0.5-CDs/CCN-5, the loading of the CDs has not been produced a large change, only a weak change in the binding energy can be found, suggesting that the CDs had an effect on the electronic structure of CCN. Fig. 2f displays the high-resolution O 1 s XPS spectra, which can be divided into two main peaks (see Table S4), corresponding to O-H and C = O, respectively[46,47]. The introduction of CDs resulted in a significant increase in the peak intensity of C = O for 0.5-CDs/CCN-5, which may be attributed to the role of oxygen-containing functional groups on the surface of CDs [48]. From the perspective optical properties, the UV–Vis diffuse reflectance spectroscopy and Mott-Schottky (M−S) curves were conducted on the prepared samples to explore the effect of C atomic doping and the introduction of CDs in CDs/CCN composite. UV–Vis diffuse reflectance spectra in Fig. 2g displays that a typical absorption band with extrapolations starting at around 450 nm can be found by the pristine CN, which is consistent with the reported work [49,50]. Compared with bare CN, there is a clear redshift trend of the absorption edge for CCN-5 and 0.5-CDs/CCN-5 in the spectral range from 450 to 500 nm with the doping of C-atoms and the introduction of CDs, and the increased band-tail related absorption band ranging from 500 to 700 nm, even up to near-infrared (NIR) region. The former results from the electronic structure optimization of CN after C-atomic doping, while the latter results from the multiple reflections of incident light in the honeycomb structure and the strong light scattering and trapping effects of CDs [51,52]. The UV–Vis diffuse reflectance spectral conversions provided in Fig. 2h determine the band gap (Eg
                        ) values of the prepared samples, which were calculated from the Kubelka-Munk function to be 2.86, 2.72 and 2.67 eV for CN, CCN-5 and 0.5-CDs/CCN-5, respectively[53]. To obtain the positions of the conduction band (CB) for the prepared samples, M−S curves were analyzed at three different frequencies of 800, 1000 and 1200 Hz (compared to the Ag/AgCl reference electrode). In Fig. 2i, the obvious positive slope comes from a typical n-type characteristic semiconductor, and the flat band potential determined as the x-intercept in the M−S diagram can be used to approximate and estimate the conduction band (CB) position of the n-type semiconductor. After conversion, the CB of CN, CCN-5 and 0.5-CDs/CCN-5 are −1.01, −1.23 and −1.28 eV, respectively. Compared with the original CN, there is a distinctly negative shift of 0.22 eV for CCN, while only minor difference for the 0.5-CDs/CCN-5 was observed, indicating that doping of C atoms is the main reason to enhance the proton reduction kinetics for photocatalytic water splitting into H2 due to the significant change for the optical properties and the band structures (Fig. S8) [54].
